Step 4 : Validating followed request JWT token
		4A:  Checking for valid token from Header in our own filter
			- Once User Logs in token is stored in SecurityContext 
			- For followed address we will use or custom filter JwtFilter which extends OncePerRequestFilter and provide implementation for doFilterInternal method
				- Here we will check if authHeader from request is null or not and authHeader starts with Bearer if both condition satisfy we will extract token using substring
				
				
		4B: Extract user name from token using utility method getUserNameFromJwtToken from JwtUtil class which takes String token as argument
			- To Extract Username
			
				a. we will need decoded signed key 
				- If we are using bas64 encoded key use this
					private Key key() {
						return Keys.hmacShaKeyFor(Decoders.BASE64.decode(SECRET_KEY));
					}
					
				- otherwise for plain text e=secret key use below
				
					private Key key() {
				        return Keys.hmacShaKeyFor(SECRET_KEY.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8));
				    }
					
				b. then we can extract username from token using this key 
				
					private Claims extractAllClaims(String token) {
					        return Jwts.parserBuilder()
					                   .setSigningKey(key())
					                   .build()
					                   .parseClaimsJws(token)
					                   .getBody();
					  }
					  
					  - with this we can extract username as well as token expiration
						
			4C : Validating token
			
				- we validate token by with username and token expiration
				
					- our util method from JwtUtility clas extract expiration from token  and validate
					
						public boolean isTokenValid(String token, String username) {
						      return username.equals(getUserNameFromJwtToken(token)) && !isTokenExpired(token);
						 }
						 
					- It extract expiration time from token useing extractAllClaims() method above from JwtUtil
					- from same extractAllClaims we extract username like below
					
					
					
					public String getUserNameFromJwtToken(String token) {
					      return extractAllClaims(token).getSubject();
					  }
				
					 public Date extractExpiration(String token) {
					     return extractAllClaims(token).getExpiration();
					  }
				
				
					  private boolean isTokenExpired(String token) {
					      return extractExpiration(token).before(new Date());
					  }
					  
					- final validate method will check 
					
						 public boolean isTokenValid(String token, String username) {
						      return username.equals(getUserNameFromJwtToken(token)) && !isTokenExpired(token);
						  }
						  
			4D : After validation in JwtFilter class
			
					- Create UsernamePasswordAuthToken and set in SecurityContextHolder, then continue remaining filterchain
					if (username != null && SecurityContextHolder.getContext().getAuthentication() == null) {

					    if (jwtUtil.isTokenValid(token, username)) {
					
					        UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken authToken =
					                new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(username, null, new ArrayList<>());
					
					        SecurityContextHolder.getContext().setAuthentication(authToken);
					    }
					}
					
					filterChain.doFilter(request, response);
					
					
